{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651257"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18437"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18437"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74718"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11155"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7763"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74718"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a chi-square test to analyse the relationship between educational level (secondary vs tertiary) and employment status (employed vs unemployed) using frequency data from 500 participants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes what a large chi-square test statistic value indicates in this analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small differences between observed frequencies","Random variation in the data","Equal distribution across all categories","Close agreement between groups","Large differences between observed and expected frequencies"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chi-square test is used when comparing categorical variables (like educational level and employment status), and is particularly useful for testing whether two categorical variables are independent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge difference between observed and expected frequencies\u003C/strong\u003E results in a large chi-square test statistic value. The chi-square test compares actual observed frequencies with the frequencies that would be expected if there was no relationship between the variables. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe larger the chi-square value, the less likely it is that the observed differences occurred by chance, potentially indicating a real relationship between the variables being studied. The other options all describe instances that would result in small chi square values. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The chi-square test is used to compare observed frequencies with expected frequencies in categorical data.","The chi-square statistic increases as the difference between observed and expected frequencies increases.","A larger chi-square value indicates a lower probability that differences occurred by chance."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T16:09:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T16:10:00+10:30"},"relationshi